VIRAL MENINGITIS - USA: (CALIFORNIA) COLLEGE STUDENTS
******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 6 Nov 2015
Source: KEYT.com [edited]
http://www.keyt.com/news/meningitis-cases-discovered-at-cal-poly/36305972


Public Health officials in San Luis Obispo County [California] are warning about cases of viral meningitis discovered at Cal Poly.

So far 5 students [in the past month] have been diagnosed with the infection. County Public Health officials stress these are cases of viral meningitis and not the more dangerous bacterial meningitis.

"People with viral meningitis usually complain they've got the worst headache of their life", says Ann McDowell, epidemiologist with the San Luis Obispo County Public Health Department, "they're feeling nauseous, they might throw up, a stiff neck, they are sensitive to light, those are the most common symptoms that you see." Meningitis, be it viral or bacterial, must be reported to the local county public health department wherever it is detected. So far no bacterial meningitis has been detected on or off the Cal Poly campus.

"Viral meningitis is contagious person to person only if you are in close proximity and sharing personal fluids", McDowell says, "so if you are sharing cups or eating utensils, or personal hygiene, or if you are hugging or kissing or in close contact with somebody you can you can spread it but it's very rare to spread viral meningitis."

Cal Poly students we spoke with say they were alerted about the viral meningitis cases on campus by the University via email. "I'm glad that I'm aware of it", says Cal Poly student Erin Clark, "but I feel like that's a pretty low percentage of people affected." "Wash your hands more, don't go to class if you're feeling real bad, professors are really understanding", adds Cal Poly student Martha Limon, "go to the health center, even if its just a cough, just go to the health center."

There's no vaccine or antibiotic for viral meningitis, treatment includes plenty of rest and fluids, full recovery can take up to 10 days.

